allcsv<-merge(twocsv,ssufian, all=TRUE)

                                                                                                                                      2020 Data Science Intern - (19001927)\nDescription\n\nInternship innovating on the long-term data and analytics strategy for the organization. The team engages in highly visible and dynamic business projects partnering closely with technology, actuarial, marketing and others to develop an integrated approach to developing and implementing data-driven solutions. The team comprises of highly skilled data scientists from a cross-functional and academic background (computer science, mathematics, physics, technology, actuarial, MBA, etc)\n\nRequired Technical and Professional Expertise\nIn process of receiving a UG or graduate degree in an analytical area such as Machine learning, Computer Science, Physics, Mathematics, Statistics, Engineering or similar.\nExperience in Analytics or other quantitative disciplines.\nExperience with modeling and analysis including machine learning, statistical analysis, operations research and management science and data mining.\nStrong interpersonal and communication skills. Must be able to explain technical concepts and analyses implications clearly to a wide audience and be able to translate business objectives into actionable analyses.\nExperience with SQL (any variations thereof), Python/PySpark and/or Scala preferred; though experience with other analytics software (SAS, STATA, MATLAB, Mathematica, R/SparklyR) is acceptable.\nUsing SQL to transform and utilize data in the data warehouse by creating, automating and documenting new tables in a post-load process.\nProven analytical and quantitative skills to use hard data and metrics to back up assumptions, develop business cases, and complete root cause analyses.\nCapable of taking responsibility for an initiative and self-starter even when assignments are vague or undefined.\nCreative in finding new solutions/designing innovative methods, systems, and processes.\nReporting:\nRole will report to AVP, Analytics Translation, Enterprise Data Analytics\n\nQualifications\n\nPreferred Tech and Prof Experience\nData Science/Technology, Financial Services, or related STEM field\nQuantitative data analysis Experience and/or coursework in Machine Learning, Statistics\nAcademic experience deploying analytical models to solve business problems\nAbility to develop experimental and analytical plans for data modeling processes\nExperience with data visualization tools\n~Housing is not provided~\n\nApplicants must be eligible to work in the U.S. without company sponsorship, now or in the future, for employment-based work authorization. H1-B and green card sponsorship is not available for this position.\n\nCompany Overview\n\nGuardian has been helping people protect their futures and secure their lives for more than 150 years. ## 2 NYU School of Medicine is one of the nation's top-ranked medical schools. For 175 years, NYU School of Medicine has trained thousands of physicians and scientists who have helped to shape the course of medical history and enrich the lives of countless people. An integral part of NYU Langone Health, the School of Medicine at its core is committed to improving the human condition through medical education, scientific research, and direct patient care. For more information, go to med.nyu.edu, and interact with us on Facebook, Twitter and Instagram.\nPosition Summary:\nWe have an exciting opportunity to join our team as a Administrative NP Coordinator for the Stroke Program at Bellevue Hospital through the NYU School of Medicine.\n\nIn this role, the successful candidate provides nursing leadership for the Bellevue Hospital Stroke Program in the development of stroke-related patient care standards, initiation and implementation of new educational programming, and expansion of stroke services consistent with the mission and goals of the Bellevue Stroke Program. Supports the leadership efforts of the Bellevue Stroke Program in collaboration with the Medical Director. Establishes priorities and implements long and short-term action plans with the Stroke Team. Participates in care coordination of stroke patients across care settings. Collaborates with interdisciplinary team to establish patient care pathways and developing the program. Participates in stroke research and development. Develops and leads Peer Review Process for the Stroke Program.\nJob Responsibilities:\nDevelopment and revision of patient care policies and treatment protocols, in collaboration with Stroke Program leadership.\nWorks collaboratively with the Stroke Team, attending physicians, house staff, consulting physician(s), and other disciplines to identify, develop, implement, create and modify as necessary an appropriate plan of care that considers potential outcomes and goals of care, maximizes patient/family preference, and that enhances quality, access, and clinical outcomes.\nProvide clinical leadership by assessing, implementing and evaluating the care provided to patients and families in the program.\nEvaluates patient responses to treatment and other therapeutic interventions. Supports service and unit level leadership by providing consultative guidance on the care of stroke patients.\nArticulate and demonstrate understanding of nursing process, patient care standards interdisciplinary collaboration, quality and performance management, patient safety, continuum of care concepts, customer service, professional practice and healthy work environments.\nPractices as a member of the allied health staff as outlined in the by-laws, rules and regulations of the Medical Staff. Acts as a professional role model to all levels of staff.\nArticulates and demonstrates nursing process when exercising responsibilities and in providing support and guidance to staff. Develops, implements, and utilizes evidence-based standards in stroke care.\nConsiders needs and behaviors of specific patient age and cultural groups in all patient care activities. Uses evidence in daily practice through implementation of established guidelines and standards of care.\nSupports the mission, philosophy, standards, goals and objectives of the institution, Departments of Nursing, Neurology, and Stroke Service. Establishes and implements program goals in collaboration with the Medical Director, and the Chief of Neurology.\nJointly develops, implements, and maintains stroke program related standards with the Stroke Team, and Nursing Practice Councils. Coordinates the Stroke Program, in collaboration with the Medical Director, the Chief of Neurology, and Stroke Coordinator.\nEnsures seamless transition of care across settings through collaborative communication with care providers.\nAssist facility based leadership in developing Stroke Center-related performance improvement initiatives that achieve improved patient outcomes.\nAssists in the development of a marketing strategy and public information plan with the Office of Public Affairs, and the Office of Strategic Business Development and Planning.\nConducts activities of the stroke program in a fiscally sound and effective manner. In collaboration with the Medical Director, ensures Stroke Program compliance with all regulatory standards, including TJC, NYSDOH, CMS, and other related regulatory agencies.\nParticipates in hospital committees and represents the hospital in outside activities.\nPromotes own professional growth and development in clinical and managerial role. Develops and implements a professional development plan.\nMaintains current expertise in neurology/neurosurgery and stroke nursing. Contributes to the development of nursing knowledge in area of practice through publication, research, and formal/informal presentations.\nServes as a clinical expert and resource for the education of peers and other health professionals related to the care and special needs of stroke patients.\nEducates patient and family to facilitate and promote healthy adjustment to change(s) in health conditions.\nAssists in the provision of interdisciplinary stroke educational programs to educate staff at all levels. Assists in the development and delivery of community education regarding advanced care planning and related topics.\nParticipates in the design, implementation, and evaluation of stroke quality improvement activities, peer review process, and research protocols.\nInitiates and/or participates in relevant research activities. Participates in organizations safety and quality initiatives as well as annual selection and evaluation of indicators relevant to stroke care.\nEvaluates success of the program through established goals and quality metrics.\nParticipates in developing, obtaining, and executing grant funded research projects.\nRecommends practice changes based on current literature, research, and evidence-based findings.\nOther duties as assigned by Stroke Program leadership.\nMinimum Qualifications:Licensure: Current registration as Professional Registered Nurse and Nurse Practitioner in NYS; DEA\nEducation: Masters degree in nursing; Board certification as an Adult or Family Nurse Practitioner\nExperience: Minimum of five years of clinical practice, preferably as NP in neurology/neurosurgery care; three or more years of progressive management or nursing leadership experience are desired. Experience with Comprehensive Stroke Center certification process is strongly preferred.\nCompetencies: All core competencies as outlined by The National Organization of Nurse Practitioner Faculties (NONPF, April 2011 and amended 2012). Evidence of ability to manage data and use of computer applications; Excellent written and verbal communication skills; Demonstrated ability to interface effectively with other disciplines and outside agencies to achieve improvement in patient outcomes, lower length of stay and efficient resource utilization. Ability to develop, implement, and sustain clinical programs; Ability to adapt to change(s); previously demonstrated ability to facilitate group processes as well as work cohesively and collaboratively as a member of the interdisciplinary team. Membership in related professional associations. Physical stamina, manual dexterity, visual and aural acuity necessary to perform all duties.\n\nQualified candidates must be able to effectively communicate with all levels of the organization.\n\nNYU School of Medicine provides its staff with far more than just a place to work. Rather, we are an institution you can be proud of, an institution where you'll feel good about devoting your time and your talents.\n\nNYU School of Medicine is an equal opportunity and affirmative action employer committed to diversity and inclusion in all aspects of recruiting and employment. All qualified individuals are encouraged to apply and will receive consideration without regard to race, color, gender, gender identity or expression, sex, sexual orientation, transgender status, gender dysphoria, national origin, age, religion, disability, military and veteran status, marital or parental status, citizenship status, genetic information or any other factor which cannot lawfully be used as a basis for an employment decision. We require applications to be completed online.\nIf you wish to view NYU School of Medicine's EEO policies, please click here. Please click here to view the Federal "EEO is the law" poster or visit https://www.dol.gov/ofccp/regs/compliance/posters/ofccpost.htm for more information. To view the Pay Transparency Notice, please click here.\nPosition Summary:\nProvides nursing leadership for the Bellevue Hospital Stroke Program in the development of stroke-related patient care standards, initiation and implementation of new educational programming, and expansion of stroke services consistent with the mission and goals of the Bellevue Stroke Program.                                                                   Epic Pharma is a generic pharmaceutical company located in Laurelton, NY. We are dedicated to developing and manufacturing generic prescription drugs in a variety of therapeutic categories in tablet, capsule and powder forms, with a focus on hard to manufacture orally administered drugs in immediate release, sustained release and delayed release forms. We are conveniently located in Laurelton, New York, within easy commute of the greater New York metro area and close to the Long Island Railroad and NYC bus service.*Analytical Research and Development Scientist Level 1Analytical Research & Development Associate*Several positions are available in the ARD Lab, requiring analyses of raw materials, in-process and solid dosage units. Bachelor’s degree in Chemistry or related science field and a 1 - 3 years lab experience, preferably in a pharmaceutical environment with solid dosage forms, is required.Candidates with at least 1 year of QC (Quality Control) experience also welcome to apply!Other requirements include:* Thorough understanding of cGMPs, specifically as they apply to a Pharmaceutical environment.* Use and troubleshooot analytical instruments and software.* Good handle on chromatographic techniques a must!* TLC, Atomic absorption, IC experience.* Wet chemistry experience preferred* Assay, dissolution and validation experience preferred* Product characterization.In addition the above for Associate level, the Level 1 Candidate must also know:* Method development & validation* Data review* Draft method validation/verification protocols and reports* All Candidates must be able to work effectively in a team in a quality oriented laboratory environment to meet company objectives and commitments.* All Candidates should have strong written and verbal communication skills and a good command of the English language.* All Candidates must demonstrate good safety practices at all times, including appropriate use of protective equipment.Epic Pharma is an equal opportunity employer and offers a competitive starting salary and benefits package, including medical/dental/vision and 401k.All candidates must be authorized to work legally in the United States on a full-time basis for ANY EMPLOYER WITHOUT SPONSORSHIP!Job Type: Full-timeExperience:Laboratory: 2 years (Preferred)Quality Control: 3 years (Preferred)Assays: 1 year (Preferred)Education:Bachelor's (Required)Language:English (Required)Additional Compensation:BonusesBenefits offered:Paid time offHealth insuranceDental insuranceOther types of insuranceRetirement benefits or accountsEmployee discountsWorkplace perks such as food/coffee and flexible work schedulesOthers

Overview\nOur Internship Program is a paid 10-week learning experience where you will be immersed in the daily environment of a thriving Fortune 250 global financial services company.\n\nYou will gain The team comprises of highly skilled data scientists from a cross-functional and academic background (computer science, mathematics, physics, technology, actuarial, MBA, etc)\n\nRequired Technical and Professional Expertise\nIn process of receiving a UG or graduate degree in an analytical area such as Machine learning, Computer Science, Physics, Mathematics, Statistics, Engineering or similar.\nExperience in Analytics or other quantitative disciplines.\nExperience with modeling and analysis including machine learning, statistical analysis, operations research and management science and data mining.\nStrong interpersonal and communication skills. Must be able to explain technical concepts and analyses implications clearly to a wide audience and be able to translate business objectives into actionable analyses.\nExperience with SQL (any variations thereof), Python/PySpark and/or Scala preferred; though experience with other analytics software (SAS, STATA, MATLAB, Mathematica, R/SparklyR) is acceptable.\nUsing SQL to transform and utilize data in the data warehouse by creating, automating and documenting new tables in a post-load process.\nProven analytical and quantitative skills to use hard data and metrics to back up assumptions, develop business cases, and complete root cause analyses.\nCapable of taking responsibility for an initiative and self-starter even when assignments are vague or undefined.\nCreative in finding new solutions/designing innovative methods, systems, and processes.\nReporting:\nRole will report to AVP, Analytics Translation, Enterprise Data Analytics\n\nQualifications\n\nPreferred Tech and Prof Experience\nData Science/Technology, Financial Services, or related STEM field\nQuantitative data analysis Experience and/or coursework in Machine Learning, Statistics\nAcademic experience deploying analytical models to solve business problems\nAbility to develop experimental and analytical plans for data modeling processes\nExperience with data visualization tools\n~Housing is not provided~\n\nApplicants must be eligible to work in the U.S. without company sponsorship, now or in the future, for employment-based work authorization. ## 2 NYU School of Medicine is one of the nation's top-ranked medical schools. For 175 years, NYU School of Medicine has trained thousands of physicians and scientists who have helped to shape the course of medical history and enrich the lives of countless people. An integral part of NYU Langone Health, the School of Medicine at its core is committed to improving the human condition through medical education, scientific research, and direct patient care. For more information, go to med.nyu.edu, and interact with us on Facebook, Twitter and Instagram.\nPosition Summary:\nWe have an exciting opportunity to join our team as a Administrative NP Coordinator for the Stroke Program at Bellevue Hospital through the NYU School of Medicine.\n\nIn this role, the successful candidate provides nursing leadership for the Bellevue Hospital Stroke Program in the development of stroke-related patient care standards, initiation and implementation of new educational programming, and expansion of stroke services consistent with the mission and goals of the Bellevue Stroke Program. Supports the leadership efforts of the Bellevue Stroke Program in collaboration with the Medical Director. Establishes priorities and implements long and short-term action plans with the Stroke Team. Participates in care coordination of stroke patients across care settings. Collaborates with interdisciplinary team to establish patient care pathways and developing the program. Participates in stroke research and development. Develops and leads Peer Review Process for the Stroke Program.\nJob Responsibilities:\nDevelopment and revision of patient care policies and treatment protocols, in collaboration with Stroke Program leadership.\nWorks collaboratively with the Stroke Team, attending physicians, house staff, consulting physician(s), and other disciplines to identify, develop, implement, create and modify as necessary an appropriate plan of care that considers potential outcomes and goals of care, maximizes patient/family preference, and that enhances quality, access, and clinical outcomes.\nProvide clinical leadership by assessing, implementing and evaluating the care provided to patients and families in the program.\nEvaluates patient responses to treatment and other therapeutic interventions. Supports service and unit level leadership by providing consultative guidance on the care of stroke patients.\nArticulate and demonstrate understanding of nursing process, patient care standards interdisciplinary collaboration, quality and performance management, patient safety, continuum of care concepts, customer service, professional practice and healthy work environments.\nPractices as a member of the allied health staff as outlined in the by-laws, rules and regulations of the Medical Staff. Acts as a professional role model to all levels of staff.\nArticulates and demonstrates nursing process when exercising responsibilities and in providing support and guidance to staff. Develops, implements, and utilizes evidence-based standards in stroke care.\nConsiders needs and behaviors of specific patient age and cultural groups in all patient care activities. Uses evidence in daily practice through implementation of established guidelines and standards of care.\nSupports the mission, philosophy, standards, goals and objectives of the institution, Departments of Nursing, Neurology, and Stroke Service. Establishes and implements program goals in collaboration with the Medical Director, and the Chief of Neurology.\nJointly develops, implements, and maintains stroke program related standards with the Stroke Team, and Nursing Practice Councils. Coordinates the Stroke Program, in collaboration with the Medical Director, the Chief of Neurology, and Stroke Coordinator.\nEnsures seamless transition of care across settings through collaborative communication with care providers.\nAssist facility based leadership in developing Stroke Center-related performance improvement initiatives that achieve improved patient outcomes.\nAssists in the development of a marketing strategy and public information plan with the Office of Public Affairs, and the Office of Strategic Business Development and Planning.\nConducts activities of the stroke program in a fiscally sound and effective manner. In collaboration with the Medical Director, ensures Stroke Program compliance with all regulatory standards, including TJC, NYSDOH, CMS, and other related regulatory agencies.\nParticipates in hospital committees and represents the hospital in outside activities.\nPromotes own professional growth and development in clinical and managerial role. Develops and implements a professional development plan.\nMaintains current expertise in neurology/neurosurgery and stroke nursing. Contributes to the development of nursing knowledge in area of practice through publication, research, and formal/informal presentations.\nServes as a clinical expert and resource for the education of peers and other health professionals related to the care and special needs of stroke patients.\nEducates patient and family to facilitate and promote healthy adjustment to change(s) in health conditions.\nAssists in the provision of interdisciplinary stroke educational programs to educate staff at all levels. Assists in the development and delivery of community education regarding advanced care planning and related topics.\nParticipates in the design, implementation, and evaluation of stroke quality improvement activities, peer review process, and research protocols.\nInitiates and/or participates in relevant research activities. Participates in organizations safety and quality initiatives as well as annual selection and evaluation of indicators relevant to stroke care.\nEvaluates success of the program through established goals and quality metrics.\nParticipates in developing, obtaining, and executing grant funded research projects.\nRecommends practice changes based on current literature, research, and evidence-based findings.\nOther duties as assigned by Stroke Program leadership.\nMinimum Qualifications:Licensure: Current registration as Professional Registered Nurse and Nurse Practitioner in NYS; DEA\nEducation: Masters degree in nursing; Board certification as an Adult or Family Nurse Practitioner\nExperience: Minimum of five years of clinical practice, preferably as NP in neurology/neurosurgery care; three or more years of progressive management or nursing leadership experience are desired. Experience with Comprehensive Stroke Center certification process is strongly preferred.\nCompetencies: All core competencies as outlined by The National Organization of Nurse Practitioner Faculties (NONPF, April 2011 and amended 2012). Evidence of ability to manage data and use of computer applications; Excellent written and verbal communication skills; Demonstrated ability to interface effectively with other disciplines and outside agencies to achieve improvement in patient outcomes, lower length of stay and efficient resource utilization. Ability to develop, implement, and sustain clinical programs; Ability to adapt to change(s); previously demonstrated ability to facilitate group processes as well as work cohesively and collaboratively as a member of the interdisciplinary team. Membership in related professional associations. Physical stamina, manual dexterity, visual and aural acuity necessary to perform all duties.\n\nQualified candidates must be able to effectively communicate with all levels of the organization.\n\nNYU School of Medicine provides its staff with far more than just a place to work. dtmw <- TermDocumentMatrix(docs )
m <- as.matrix(dtmw)
v <- sort(rowSums(m),decreasing=TRUE)
d <- data.frame(word = names(v),freq=v)
head(d, 10)
##            word freq
## data       data 2528
## work       work  918
## experi   experi  894
## team       team  816
## will       will  756
## learn     learn  741
## develop develop  719
## busi       busi  671
## analyt   analyt  593
## model     model  587

Generate the Word cloud

The important key skill sets can be illustrated as a word cloud as follow :

set.seed(1234)
wordcloud(words = d$word, freq = d$freq, min.freq = 1,
          max.words=200, random.order=FALSE, rot.per=0.35, 
          colors=brewer.pal(8, "Dark2"))

Sentiment Analysis

toolskills <- clean_allcsv2 %>%
    mutate(R = grepl("\\bR\\b,", Job_Description, ignore.case=TRUE)) %>%
    mutate(python = grepl("Python", Job_Description, ignore.case=TRUE)) %>%
    mutate(SQL = grepl("SQL", Job_Description, ignore.case=TRUE)) %>%
    mutate(hadoop = grepl("hadoop", Job_Description, ignore.case=TRUE)) %>%
    mutate(perl = grepl("perl", Job_Description, ignore.case=TRUE)) %>%
    mutate(matplotlib = grepl("matplotlib", Job_Description, ignore.case=TRUE)) %>%
    mutate(Cplusplus = grepl("C++", Job_Description, fixed=TRUE)) %>%
